1. Introduction¶

This is project as part of Data Analysis nanodegree. I have chosen to work with the Titanic dataset after spending some time poking around and looking at other resources made by Kagglers for inspiration. I focused on data analysis process as described during lectures of the course "Investigate a Dataset". I did a lot of data manipulation as well as some illustrative data visualisations along the way.

In this challenge, I will complete the analysis of what sorts of people were likely to survive. In particular, I will apply the tools of data analysis learned during the course to explore which passengers survived the tragedy.

2. Brainstorm Questions¶

First some basic questions:

1.) Who were the passengers on the Titanic? (Ages,Gender,Class,..etc)

2.) Where did the passengers come from?

3.) What deck were the passengers on and how does that relate to their class?

4.) Who was alone and who was with family?

5.) Do families sink or swim together?

Then we'll dig deeper, with a broader question:

6.) What factors helped someone survive the sinking?

3.2. Feature Engineering¶

The first variable which catches my attention is age and sex name because we can break it down into additional meaningful variables which can feed predictions or be used in the creation of additional new variables. Let's do some feature engineering!

1. Age¶

In [22]:
##  First let's make a function to sort through the sex 
##  We'll treat anyone as under 16 as a child

def male_female_child (passenger):
    
    age, sex = passenger
    if age < 16 :
        return 'child'
    else:
        return sex

3. Families¶

Now that we’ve taken care of splitting passenger name into some new variables, we can take it a step further and make some new family variables. First we’re going to make a family size variable based on number of siblings/spouse(s) (maybe someone has more than one spouse?) and number of children/parents.

In [27]:
## Create new feature FamilySize as a combination of SibSp and Parch
titanic_dat['FamilySize'] = titanic_dat['SibSp'] + titanic_dat['Parch'] + 1

Now we know that if the Alone column is anything but 0, then the passenger had family aboard and wasn't alone. So let's change the column now so that if the value is greater than 0, we know the passenger was with his/her family, otherwise they were alone.

In [28]:
# Create new feature IsAlone from FamilySize
titanic_dat['IsAlone'] = 0
titanic_dat.loc[titanic_dat['FamilySize'] == 1, 'IsAlone'] = 1

# Mapping FamilySize
def discretise_family_size(fam): 
    if fam == 1:
        return 'singleton'
    elif fam < 5 and fam > 1:
        return 'small'
    else:
        return 'large'
In [31]:
titanic_dat['FamilySizeD'] = titanic_dat[['SibSp']].applymap(discretise_family_size)

5. Passenger Title¶

We can break passenger name down into additional meaningful variables which can feed predictions or be used in the creation of additional new variables. For instance, passenger title is contained within the passenger name variable and we can use it to represent title.

In [33]:
import re as re

def get_title(name):
    title_search = re.search(' ([A-Za-z]+)\.', name)

    # If the title exists, extract and return it.|
    if title_search:
        return title_search.group(1)
    return ""
In [34]:
titanic_dat['Title'] = titanic_dat['Name'].apply(get_title)

3.4. Missing Values¶

Missing Values Imputations :¶

Now we're ready to start exploring missing data and rectifying it through imputation. There are a number of different ways we could go about doing this. Given the small size of the dataset, we probably should not opt for deleting either entire observations (rows) or variables (columns) containing missing values. We're left with the option of either replacing missing values with a sensible values given the distribution of the data, e.g., the mean, median or mode. Finally, we could go with prediction later on.

The age feature has some missing values. While there are many ways to fill these missing values, using the mean or median of the rest of the values is quite common in such cases. I have calculated the mean, the standard deviation of the Age column and use that value to populate the missing values.

The embarked feature has some missing value. I have filled those with the most occurred value ( 'S' ). I carried out some data visualisation e.g. box plots, kde plots (not shown here) to guide my decisions to impute values with mean/median.

In [48]:
# We have plenty of missing values in this feature. 
# Generate random numbers between (mean - std) and (mean + std).

#Now let's open it with pandas
import numpy as np

age_avg = titanic_dat_1['Age'].mean()
age_std = titanic_dat_1['Age'].std()
age_null_count = titanic_dat_1['Age'].isnull().sum()
age_null_random_list = np.random.randint(age_avg - age_std, age_avg + age_std, size = age_null_count)
titanic_dat_1['Age'][np.isnan(titanic_dat_1['Age'])] = age_null_random_list
titanic_dat_1['Age'] = titanic_dat_1['Age'].astype(int)

#titanic_dat_1['Age'].isnull().sum()

# Mapping Embarked
# Remove all NULLS in the Fare column and create a new feature CategoricalFare
titanic_dat_1['Embarked'] = titanic_dat_1['Embarked'].fillna('S')
titanic_dat_1['Embarked'] = titanic_dat_1['Embarked'].map( {'S': 0, 'C': 1, 'Q': 2} ).astype(int)

## Remove all NULLS in the Cabin column
titanic_dat_1['Cabin'] = titanic_dat_1['Cabin'].fillna(0)

## Mapping Sex
titanic_dat_1['Sex'] = titanic_dat_1['Sex'].map( {'female': 0, 'male': 1} ).astype(int)

## Mapping titles
title_mapping = {"Mr": 1, "Miss": 2, "Mrs": 3, "Master": 4, "Rare": 5}
titanic_dat_1['Title'] = titanic_dat_1['Title'].map(title_mapping)
#titanic_dat_2['Title'] = titanic_dat_2['Title'].fillna(0)

## Mapping Fare
## Remove all NULLS in the Fare column and create a new feature CategoricalFare
titanic_dat_1['Fare'] = titanic_dat_1['Fare'].fillna(titanic_dat_1['Fare'].median())

titanic_dat_1['Fare'] = titanic_dat_1['Fare'].astype(int)

3.7. Feature's Relationships¶

Often we have features that are highly correlated and thus provide redundant information. By eliminating highly correlated features we can avoid a predictive bias for the information contained in these features. This also shows us, that when we want to make statements about the of specific features, we need to keep in mind that just because they are suitable to predicting an outcome they are not necessarily causal - they could simply be correlated with causal factors. This could be very important criterion in fitting predictive models late in the course.

4.1. Passengers Gender¶

Passengers geneder is considered a significant factor to consider due to the tradtional belief that in times of emergencies that deal with the sinking of a ship women and children were considered priority to be put on life boats to be brought to safety. So the expectation would be that males would be the majority of the deaths on the titanic. So the first factor to be considered is to consider how many females and males were on the titanic.

## Function to convert fares prices into catagories 
def convert_far_in_cat(fare):
    if fare == 0:
        return 'low'
    elif fare == 1:
        return 'medium'
    elif fare == 2:
        return 'high'
    else:
        return 'very high'

Conclusions::¶

When looking at the passengers’ data we see that we can split it into specific groups based on age (Child and adult age groups), gender, embarked cities, location of cabins and passenger classes. When separating the passengers into these groups it allowed us to investigate survival for each of the groups and a combination of the groups that passengers match with.

  • When taking in the column 'survived' we can see that a larger population of passengers didn't survive versus passengers that did survive.
  • Comparing the survivability of the genders we see a significant survivability patterns between female and male passengers.
  • Regardless of class the result of being a male in any class dramatically decreased chances of survival. Survival rates for the 3rd class were substantially lower. But maybe this effect was caused by the large amount of men in the 3rd class in combination with the women and children first policy.
  • Deep investigations into data showed being a male or being in 3rd class were both not favourable for survival.
  • We also observed that the majority of passengers come from Southampton. Investigating more into Southampton we were able to disentangle that the majority of Southampton that boarded the Titanic were PClass 3 and a more equal split between PClass 1 and 2. In terms of Queenstown it was predominately PClass 3, while Cherbourg has a pretty close split between PClass 1 and 3.
  • We also checked if class of the passengers had an effect on their survival rate, since the movie Titanic popularised the notion that the 3rd class passengers did not do as well as their 1st and 2nd class counterparts. Indeed from this data It was evident that survival rates for the 3rd class are substantially lower. This could be partly explained as there were large number of men in the 3rd class in combination with the women and children first policy.
  • We observed a general trend that the older the passenger was, the less likely they survived. So quite a few more people died than those who survived.
  • We see in this graph that Family passengers had a more chance of survival compared to passengers that traveled alone which only have a quite less survival rate.
  • We saw a significant survival probability among the different passenger classes (PClasses). The survival of children falls closely to adult females which is to be expected as the women and children priority for lifeboats as compared to every man for themselves after lifeboats are filled with females and children for male adults.
  • Using a point graph with line connecting the points we are able to see more clearly the survival rate for each class age and how the lower the passenger classes lower the chance of survival given the passenger data from the Titanic dataset.

What next ?¶

We have just explored Titanic data set by data manipulation and visualisations. However, in order to back up our findings we need to carry out some sort of statistical tests so we can draw some sort of fairly straightforward conclusions from this data. For example being a woman, being in 1st class and being of a child all factors that could boost your chances of survival during this disaster. What we can do is to use predictive models to predict whether a given passenger would survive the disaster. This is where machine learning comes in: we will build a programme that learns from the sample data to predict whether a given passenger would survive.

  • Good test set performance of a statistical learning method requires low variance as well as low squared bias. This is referred to as a trade-off because it is easy to obtain a method with extremely low bias but high variance or a method with very low variance but high bias. The challenge lies in finding a method for which both the variance and the squared bias are low. This trade-off is one of the most important recurring themes in data analysis process.
  • Number of machine learning algorithms can be applied to data. Staring from some sort of simple models (linear model, logistic regression) to really advance level predictive models (Random Forest, Neural Network , SVM, Naive Bays etc..). Once we have number of models for our data set, we can look at the accuracy for all of our models. The best fitting model can be used for final interpretation of our dataset. This would enable of which above-mentioned factors/features finally contributed to survival of the passenger on titanic.
  • Furhtermore, We can fine-tune the machine learning algorithms to achieve better accuracy on this data set, design our own statistical models using python, discover more fascinating stories of passengers whose survival does not match the model, and apply all of these techniques to any other data set. Someone rightly said when it comes to machine learning, the possibilities are endless and the opportunities are titanic.

6. Limitations¶

It's important to identify and acknowledge the limitation of the study. Keeping in mind this analysis is done with statistical calculations and not statistical testing many opinions in this project can only be considered trend observations and correlation observations. The discussion for limitation of this study could be exhaustive. However, I will describe some of salient features had they have rectified we could have different interpretation of our analysis for given dataset.

The conclusion made based on this analysis could be having some caveats.

  • Correlation and Exploratory Studies Correlation doesn't imply causation. My conclusions are based on exploratory and correlative analysis on the provided data set. So our first goal should be to determine whether the data provide evidence of an association between different features and survival based on some statistics evidence.
  • Missing values. To begin with the Titanic data set we had number of features with lots of missing data. For instance in case of age’ column there were values for 714 passengers, for ‘Cabin’ column 204 individuals were represented whereas ‘Embarked’ columns have 889 elements out of the total count of passengers of 891.
  • Passenger age, gender, cabin location, socioeconomically class. Titanic dataset focuses on mostly on passenger age, gender, cabin location, socioeconomically class. However, it doesn’t bring more subjective aspects into light that may influence survivability of the passenger. While we know limitedly cabin location this doesn't necessarily mean all passengers were in their cabins at the time of the Titanic hitting an iceberg even if the time the ship hit the iceberg is at night it is hard to assume everyone would be soundly asleep in their assigned cabins the minute the Titanic hits the iceberg.
  • Passengers Age. Age can very well effect a chance of survivability as it can effect how fast a passenger would respond to an emergency or if they are considered a priority when they get to the lifeboats or even if they were mobile enough to do anything during the emergency that can get them to safety during the sinking of the Titanic. Looking at the graph "Age Distribution by Survival" we can see an overview of ages of passengers showing the age groups of non-survivors and the survivors and we see on the non-surivors group that the IQR trended to older passengers while the survivors group had an IQR favoring younger passengers.
  • Cities of Embarkment. Cities have their own socioeconomical distribution so the disembarks definably influence the socioeconomical population of the passengers in the Titanic. Looking into more detail the disembark locations and their effects to the PClasses in the Titanic we can reference the "Passenger Distribution of Disembark Locations".
  • Using sample instead of the population. It's known, that there were 1317 passengers and 885 crewmembers on the board of Titanic. Our data set represent just 891 persons. There is no clear mention of the crewmembers in the data set - so either they are not in the data set or they are hidden among the passengers of the 1, 2 and 3 classes. If the crewmembers are represented in our data set, the overall statistic might be distorted.
  • Passengers Traveling with Family or Alone. We have witnessed a survival is pulled towards if people are travelling with their family instead on their own. There was a significant increase in survival rate when traveling with family.
  • Passengers Journey Origins Looking at the graph we see C, Q, S corresponds to Cherbourg, Queenstown, Southampton. We see quickly Southampton accounts for the majority of the passengers that boarded the Titanic accounting for at least 350 PClass 3 passengers, at least 150 PClass 2 passengers and at least 100 PClass 1 passengers. Southampton from the way it embarked a large amount of passengers it is very possible Southampton was the largest city to disembark for the Titanic and had a fairly wide range of different reasons, it could be that a person doesn't wish to leave a loved one that can't make it out themself or family members help each other as a group and overcome obstacles that couldn't be done alone. Firstly we see from the graph "Passenger Distribution (Alone versus Family)" we see that most people did travel alone but people who did travel with family was still a decent amount, accounting for about 350 passengers out of the 891 passengers in the dataset.
